    "content-canon-sn22-86": {
        "type": "content",
        "title": "SN 22.86: Anuradha Sutta",
        "description": "",
        "tags": "ebts buddha function sn sutta philosophy",
        "category": "canon",
        "boost": 4,
        "authors": ["Joseph Goldstein"],
        "translator": "Bhikkhu Bodhi",
        "content": "Who was the Buddha in his own words? In this story, he calls himself the ãTathagataã or ãTruth-Arriverã, and he responds to a question on what will become of him after his death. The Buddha explains that he doesnãt talk in such terms, as he has overcome all such notions as ãI am the bodyã or ãI am the mindã so how could such a question ever be answered? He ends the discourse by famously saying that all he teaches is suffering and the end of suffering, thus redirecting our attention from empty philosophical musings to the things that matter most. ",
        "url": "/content/canon/sn22.86"
    },
  
    
    
    "content-canon-sn22-95": {
        "type": "content",
        "title": "SN 22.95: A Lump of Foam",
        "description": "",
        "tags": "sn philosophy vipassana emptiness problems chaplaincy",
        "category": "canon",
        "boost": 4,
        "authors": [],
        "translator": "Bhikkhu Bodhi",
        "content": " Now suppose that in the autumnãwhen itãs raining in fat, heavy dropsãa water bubble were to appear &amp; disappear on the water, and a man with sight were to see it. To him it would appear empty, void, without substance: for what substance could there be in a bubble? In the same way, a man with wisdom sees a feeling. To him it would appear empty, void, without substance: for what substance could there be in a feeling? ",
        "url": "/content/canon/sn22.95"
    },
  
    
    
