    "content-monographs-behave-sapolsky-robert": {
        "type": "content",
        "title": "Behave: The Biology of Humans at Our Best and Worst",
        "description": "",
        "tags": "biology khandha thought problems emotions power people science",
        "category": "monographs",
        "boost": 4,
        "authors": ["Robert M. Sapolsky"],
        "translator": "",
        "content": " If we accept that there will always be sides, itãs a nontrivial to-do list item to always be on the side of angels. Distrust essentialism. Keep in mind that what seems like rationality is often just rationalization, playing catch-up with subterranean forces that we never suspect. Focus on the larger, shared goals. Practice perspective taking. Individuate, individuate, individuate. [ãÎ] You donãt have to choose between being scientific and being compassionate. A magisterial and heart-felt survey of neuroscience, psychology, and biology which paints a broad but rigorous picture of how and why humans act the way they doãfor better or for worseãand what we (individual meatbags) can do to be our best selves. ",
        "url": "/content/monographs/behave_sapolsky-robert"
    },
  
    
    
    "content-monographs-behind-the-beautiful-forevers-boo-katherine": {
        "type": "content",
        "title": "Behind the Beautiful Forevers: Life, Death, and Hope in a Mumbai Undercity",
        "description": "",
        "tags": "society places india mumbai people economics becon class caste craft journalism future power refugees renunciation",
        "category": "monographs",
        "boost": 4,
        "authors": ["Katherine Boo"],
        "translator": "",
        "content": " ãÎand maybe because of the boiling April sun, he thought about water and ice. Water and ice were made of the same thing. He thought most people were made of the same thing, too. He himself was probably a little different from the corrupt people around him. Ice was distinct fromãand in his view, better thanãwhat it was made of. He wanted to be better than what he was made of. In Mumbaiãs dirty water, he wanted to be ice. A haunting and beautiful portrait of humanity, Behind the Beautiful Forevers reads more like a novel than nonfiction. But journalism it is. Of the highest order. Written after three years of observations and interviews in a small slum of Mumbai, the book follows a few locals as they build their lives amidst the devastating poverty just behind the Beautiful Forevers. ",
        "url": "/content/monographs/behind-the-beautiful-forevers_boo-katherine"
    },
  
    
    
