        "content": "Who was the Buddha?ãBuddhaã (properly speaking) refers, not to a single individual, but rather to a category of beings: those who have, through their own effort, attained complete enlightenment. But, more typically, ãthe Buddhaã refers to the Sakyan prince who, in the 5th century BCE Gangetic Plain, first rediscovered nibbána and taught the way for attaining it. Over 500 million people now worship the Buddha as their teacher, but the Buddha was no God. Indeed, itãs even said that a Buddha can only arise as a humanãnever as a deity (deva)ã because only the human realm balances the misfortunes and mistakes of life which are necessary to motivate the practice, with the ease and discernment which allow it to ripen. But while the Buddha was born a man, a man he did not remain. Through his superior striving and wisdom (over countless eons) he was able to transcend gender, caste, creed, identities, views, suffering and even death itself and to teach others how to transcend themselves too. We call such a teacher, ãBuddha.ã PrerequisitesIf youãre looking for a quick and inspiring biography of the Buddha, I recommend The Biography of Shakyamuni Buddha by Master Hsing Yun. This course goes beyond the basics to reading the primary sources themselves, and therefore requires some comfort reading the Early Buddhist Texts. Course MaterialsThis syllabus has no associated lectures. It weaves together several, free books, mostly on the Páli texts. TextbooksMain Anthology The Life of the Buddha ã Bhikkhu ûáÃ¿amoli Thera (.pdf) This classic, quirky anthology gives a good presentation of the Canonical account of the Buddhaãs life. It will be the primary biography used in this course, and we will follow the bookãs ordering of events. Other AnthologiesTo supplement ûanamoliãs judicious selections from the Páli Canon, we will use these anthologies to underline a couple themes I think worth dwelling on: Teacher of the Devas ã Susan E. Jootla (.pdf) (.epub) To understand the Buddhist cosmology requires seeing the way the Gods and the Buddha related with one another. Buddha, My Refuge ã Laurence Khantipalo Mills (.pdf) While it is important to mine the Páli literature for historical and mythological details, it is also important to not lose sight of the Buddhaãs extraordinary personal qualities, explained in this anthology through the nine characteristics of the Buddha. Primary TextsThereãs one significant primary text in this course, but it isnãt an early text. The Nidánakathá: Introduction to the Játaka Stories (.pdf) (.epub) This traditional Páli commentary contains one of the first systematic biographies of the Buddha and formed the basis for many of the later hagiographies. While not necessarily a reliable source of information about the historical Buddha himself, it is of critical importance for understanding the myths and stories about the Buddha which persist today. Academic WorksA number of articles and essays will be weaved in throughout the course. Weãll also be reading these two, free books: Original Versions of Some Entries for the Encyclopedia of Buddhism ã Peter Harvey (.pdf) A collection of Encyclopedia articles introducing the Buddha from one of the English languageãs best authors of rigorous introductions. The Genesis of the Bodhisattva Ideal ã Bhikkhu Análayo (.pdf) In this monograph, the renowned scholar of early Buddhism explores what the early literature can tell us about how the Buddha became the Buddha: a topic of extraordinary importance in later centuries. Course OutlineIãve sequenced the above books into an inter-woven, narrative arc which I (at least!) find compelling. If I were to actually teach this course, Iãd perhaps meet twice per week for 13 weeks. The readings below have been bunched together according to this hypothetical schedule, but for individual study youãre of course welcome to work through the readings as you like. Introduction [Entries - Peter Harvey] The Early Buddhist Concept of the Buddha  [Entries] Past and Future Buddhas  [E] Dates of the Buddha [Nidanakatha: The Introduction to the Jatakas] The Introduction by T. W. Rhys Davids [E] The Buddhaãs Historical Context Part 1: Becoming the Buddha [Life of the Buddha] Birth and Childhood  DN 30: The Marks of a Great Man (.pdf)   This mythic text gives the 32 characteristics of Gotamaãs body, which,legend has it, marked him for greatness at an early age. Note that some of the Suttas are not as early as others!    On the Origins of the 32 Marks of a Great Man ã Nathan McGovern (.pdf)   Politics of the Buddhaãs Genitals ã Bhante Sujato (.pdf)  [E] The Buddhaãs Family  Did the Buddha Really Have a Wife and Son? ã Matthew Gindin (.pdf)  [Life] The Struggle for Enlightenment  [Bodhisattva Ideal - Analayo] Chapter 1: Gautama as a Bodhisattva  [Nidanakatha] The Middle Epoch     Note especially any contrasts to the earlier texts.     [E] The Bodhisattva Career in the Theravada [Bodhisattva] Chapter 2: Meeting the Previous Buddha  The Sumedhakathá in Páli Literature and Its Relation to the Northern Buddhist Textual Tradition ã Junko Matsumura (.pdf)   [Nidanakatha] The Distant Epoch  [Buddha, My Refuge] Introduction [Life] After the Enlightenment  Epithets of the Buddha (.jpeg) (.jpeg)   The Meaning of the Word Tathágata According to the Páli Commentaries: Text and Introduction ã Bhikkhu Bodhi (.pdf) (.pdf)   Tathágata ã Bhikkhu Análayo (.pdf)   The Weary Buddha: Why the Buddha Nearly Couldnãt Be Bothered ã David Webster (.pdf) (.pdf)  [Entries] Pratyeka-buddhas [Entries] Optional: The Four Ennobling Truths  [Refuge] ArahaÃ¿  [Life] Spreading the Dhamma [L] The Two Chief Disciples  [L] Anathapindika: Feeder of the Poor  [N] The Last Epoch [Refuge] sammá-sambuddho DN 28: Inspiring Confidence (.pdf) Part 2: Establishing the Religion [E] Review: The Story of the Buddha  [Teacher of the Devas] Introduction: The Devas  [Life] Formation of the Order of Nuns  A Whisper in the Silence: Nuns Before Mahápajápatá¨ ã Liz Williams (.pdf) (.pdf)   Mahápajápatá¨ãs Going Forth in the Madhyama-ágama ã Bhikkhu Análayo (.pdf)  [Refuge] Vijjá-caraÃ¿a-sampanno  Tevijja-Vacchagotta Sutta ã Bhikkhu Análayo (.pdf)  [L] The Quarrel at Kosambi  [R] Sugato  [L] End of the First Twenty Years  MN 35: Cé¨Ã¡ñasaccaka Sutta (.pdf)  [T] Teaching the Devas  [R] Locavidé¨  [L] The Middle Period  [E] The Buddhaãs Style of Teaching  [R] Anuttaro purisa-damma-sárathi [L] The Person  MN 91: With Brahmáyu (.pdf)   The Buddha Was Bald ã Eisel Mazard (.pdf)  [L] The Doctrine  [E] Anatman  [R] Satthá deva-manussánaÃ¿ [T] Devas Honor the Buddha  [L] Devadatta  [R] Buddho [L] Old Age [E] The Buddha and Cakravartins  Review: [T] Devas in the Buddhaãs Career  [L] The Last Year  Sé¨karamaddava: The Buddhaãs Last Meal ã John D. Ireland (.pdf) (.pdf)  [E] Relics of the Buddha  [R] Bhagava  [E] Early Symbols of the Buddha [L] The First Council [T] Liberation and Conclusion Epilogue: The Far Future [Bodhisattva] Maitreya ",
